{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T23-11-37-594Z","slug":"beware-the-single-purpose-people","locale":"fr","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T23:11:47.678Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2025-04-03--beware-the-single-purpose-people/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2025-04-03--beware-the-single-purpose-people/fr/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/beware-the-single-purpose-people/fr/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T23-11-37-594Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"589549661808bbda140a93d1cc1d1b94e45f65803955211732aca6ca7dd257ab","outputHash":"12071d3209233082103739bb10922d322554147b690261c6175b80c6cc196124","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article argues that the Single‑Responsibility Principle (SRP) is valuable when applied with judgment, but “Single‑Purpose People” misuse it by equating “small” with “cohesive,” leading to over‑fragmented codebases. It illustrates how strict line‑count rules and excessive modularization—especially in React/Redux‑style architectures—produce file‑system sprawl, tangled dependencies, brittle tests, and slowed development velocity. The tone is a critical analysis peppered with vivid metaphors (e.g., “file system shrapnel,” “Rube Goldberg architecture”) that frame the problem as a form of architectural violence. The intended audience is software engineers, architects, and team leads who care about pragmatic design and want to avoid the productivity drain caused by obsessive adherence to SRP. The piece concludes with a pragmatic alternative: prioritize cohesion and logical grouping over maximal atomization.","totalInputTokens":6610,"totalOutputTokens":2836,"totalCacheReadTokens":1024,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":9080,"totalCostUsd":0.0007682699999999999,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","chunkSize":"10p","total